00:03:04.790 --> 00:03:07.080
You know, my nonprofit.

00:03:07.080 --> 00:03:09.170
Hip-Hope Chess Federation,
fuses music, chess,

00:03:09.170 --> 00:03:11.230
and martial arts to
promote unity, strategy,

00:03:11.230 --> 00:03:12.930
and nonviolence.

00:03:12.930 --> 00:03:16.280
Essentially, when
I was young, I was

00:03:16.280 --> 00:03:18.120
obsessed with kung fu films.

00:03:18.120 --> 00:03:20.740
I was obsessed with
the television show

00:03:20.740 --> 00:03:22.700
"Kung Fu," Bruce Lee films.

00:03:22.700 --> 00:03:25.400
And when I got
older, I started--

00:03:25.400 --> 00:03:28.280
my first interview,
my first job writing,

00:03:28.280 --> 00:03:32.690
was to interview Eazy-E for
my high school newspaper.

00:03:32.690 --> 00:03:34.680
And at the time, I was
kind of hustling him.

00:03:34.680 --> 00:03:35.527
He didn't know.

00:03:35.527 --> 00:03:38.110
Like, they had just dropped the
record and I called over there

00:03:38.110 --> 00:03:40.300
and I was like, hello,
is Eazy-E there?

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:41.340
And they were like, no.

00:03:41.340 --> 00:03:42.610
I left him a message.

00:03:42.610 --> 00:03:44.900
I was like, I'm a big-time
writer from the Bay Area.

00:03:44.900 --> 00:03:46.290
I'd love to connect with him.

00:03:46.290 --> 00:03:47.560
Can you have him call me?

00:03:47.560 --> 00:03:50.070
And then when I came
back, my mom was like,

00:03:50.070 --> 00:03:52.170
oh, this boy named Eric
left a message for you

00:03:52.170 --> 00:03:53.240
from Los Angeles.

00:03:53.240 --> 00:03:54.432
And I was like, really?

00:03:54.432 --> 00:03:55.140
So then I called.

00:03:55.140 --> 00:03:55.980
He was like, hello?

00:03:55.980 --> 00:03:57.040
And it was his house.

00:03:57.040 --> 00:03:58.180
It was his home number.

00:03:58.180 --> 00:04:00.240
I was like, uh,
yeah, I really like

00:04:00.240 --> 00:04:01.570
the record "Boyz in the Hood."

00:04:01.570 --> 00:04:03.630
I think it would be good
if I did a story on you.

00:04:03.630 --> 00:04:05.190
So he was like, OK.

00:04:05.190 --> 00:04:09.950
So over the course of some
weeks, I keep talking with him,

00:04:09.950 --> 00:04:11.700
and I interviewed him.

00:04:11.700 --> 00:04:14.334
My mom was a secretary,
so she had all the stuff

00:04:14.334 --> 00:04:16.209
that you could hook up
the phones at the time

00:04:16.209 --> 00:04:17.490
to record interviews.

00:04:17.490 --> 00:04:19.410
So I recorded this
interview with him.

00:04:19.410 --> 00:04:22.600
And we just became like,
it was this odd friendship

00:04:22.600 --> 00:04:25.520
between this gangster rapper
and this suburban black kid.

00:04:25.520 --> 00:04:29.250
And I remember one day,
he's like, so hey, man,

00:04:29.250 --> 00:04:32.640
is this going on
"The Chronicle"?

00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:35.550
My manager meant to
ask me to ask you,

00:04:35.550 --> 00:04:36.700
is it in "The Examiner"?

00:04:36.700 --> 00:04:38.600
Like, who do you write for?

00:04:38.600 --> 00:04:41.980
And I was like, I
gotta be honest, man.

00:04:41.980 --> 00:04:45.610
I'm just a 17-year-old kid, man.

00:04:45.610 --> 00:04:47.240
I just really like your music.

00:04:47.240 --> 00:04:49.290
And the song really
wasn't a hit.

00:04:49.290 --> 00:04:52.070
I mean, "Boyz in the Hood" was
only like maybe a month old.

00:04:52.070 --> 00:04:53.574
So he was like, I don't care.

00:04:53.574 --> 00:04:54.240
This is awesome.

00:04:54.240 --> 00:04:55.360
Let's do the story.

00:04:55.360 --> 00:04:57.670
So I did the story,
and we stayed cool

00:04:57.670 --> 00:04:58.600
until he passed away.

00:04:58.600 --> 00:05:01.910
But that's how I got
my start writing.

00:05:01.910 --> 00:05:04.547
And so this was before
hip-hop magazines existed.

00:05:04.547 --> 00:05:05.880
You know, there was no "Source."

00:05:05.880 --> 00:05:08.100
There was no AllHipHop.com,
no World Star.

00:05:08.100 --> 00:05:09.370
None of that stuff existed.

00:05:09.370 --> 00:05:11.572
So the more that I started
listening to hip-hop,

00:05:11.572 --> 00:05:13.780
around that same time, I'm
listening to Public Enemy,

00:05:13.780 --> 00:05:15.760
and I'm hearing them say things
like, "no matter what the name,

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:18.250
we're all the same, pieces
in one big chess game."

00:05:18.250 --> 00:05:21.810
And so lyrics like that, because
I liked chess-- and I do,

00:05:21.810 --> 00:05:22.460
I love chess.

00:05:22.460 --> 00:05:23.668
I'm just not that good at it.

00:05:23.668 --> 00:05:27.400
So do not think I'm like going
to wow you on the boards at all

00:05:27.400 --> 00:05:29.020
ever.

00:05:29.020 --> 00:05:31.170
But the reason I liked
it is because I started

00:05:31.170 --> 00:05:33.820
learning things about life,
about patience and things

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:34.527
like that.

00:05:34.527 --> 00:05:36.610
And the more I listened
to hop-hop over the years,

00:05:36.610 --> 00:05:41.130
I made this bank in my
head of what was what.

00:05:41.130 --> 00:05:45.520
And so I started realizing
that these connections were

00:05:45.520 --> 00:05:47.580
really deep.

00:05:47.580 --> 00:05:51.780
Later on, I created the
Hop-Hop Chess Federation, 2006,

00:05:51.780 --> 00:05:54.342
and the way that happened is
I went for an author visit

00:05:54.342 --> 00:05:55.800
for one of my other
previous books,

00:05:55.800 --> 00:05:57.216
which was called
"Lyrical Swords."

00:05:57.216 --> 00:05:58.450
It was my first book.

00:05:58.450 --> 00:06:00.660
And so I went into
the juvenile hall.

00:06:00.660 --> 00:06:02.780
I was bombing,
because they wanted

00:06:02.780 --> 00:06:06.882
me to talk about journalism as
a career, and none of the kids

00:06:06.882 --> 00:06:07.840
cared about journalism.

00:06:07.840 --> 00:06:09.504
They're like, you
ever met Snoop Dogg?

00:06:09.504 --> 00:06:10.920
I talked to him
on the phone once.

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:12.360
You ever met so and so?

00:06:12.360 --> 00:06:14.190
They didn't care
about writing at all.

00:06:14.190 --> 00:06:19.272
So I was like, all right,
so, do any of you guys

00:06:19.272 --> 00:06:20.230
know how to play chess?

00:06:20.230 --> 00:06:22.606
Because I just started
teaching my son

00:06:22.606 --> 00:06:24.480
chess, and I just happened
to have the pieces

00:06:24.480 --> 00:06:25.760
in a bag in my thing.

00:06:25.760 --> 00:06:27.620
So I'm like, I'm going to waste
time teaching these kids chess,

00:06:27.620 --> 00:06:29.060
because I'm sure they
don't know how to play.

00:06:29.060 --> 00:06:30.840
I said, who here knows
how to play chess?

00:06:30.840 --> 00:06:32.500
And like 85% of the room.

00:06:32.500 --> 00:06:37.612
I was like, OK, so,
who's the best in here?

00:06:37.612 --> 00:06:39.820
I only want you keep your
hand up if you're the best.

00:06:39.820 --> 00:06:40.600
Only the best.

00:06:40.600 --> 00:06:42.421
And then only a few
hands went down.

00:06:42.421 --> 00:06:44.046
I was like, here's
what we're gonna do.

00:06:44.046 --> 00:06:45.837
We're going to have a
tournament right now.

00:06:45.837 --> 00:06:47.637
Whoever wins will get a book.

00:06:47.637 --> 00:06:48.720
They were like, all right.

00:06:48.720 --> 00:06:50.010
So everybody circles up.

00:06:50.010 --> 00:06:52.709
So the first game, these
two black kids are playing,

00:06:52.709 --> 00:06:54.750
and there was this white
kid who was in the hall,

00:06:54.750 --> 00:06:56.150
and he was in the inner circle.

00:06:56.150 --> 00:06:58.150
So the guy was getting
ready to move his knight,

00:06:58.150 --> 00:07:00.499
and he was like, don't
move your knight.

00:07:00.499 --> 00:07:02.040
And dude was like,
shut up white boy.

00:07:02.040 --> 00:07:03.427
Nobody asked you nothing.

00:07:03.427 --> 00:07:05.760
So he moves his knight, loses
his queen, loses the game.

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:08.301
And then everybody's like, oh,
the white boy knows what's up.

00:07:08.301 --> 00:07:10.230
We gotta pay
attention when he's--

00:07:10.230 --> 00:07:12.859
So then when I first
asked who the best was,

00:07:12.859 --> 00:07:14.150
there was this kid in the back.

00:07:14.150 --> 00:07:14.691
He was obese.

00:07:14.691 --> 00:07:16.436
He was like 300 pounds.

00:07:16.436 --> 00:07:17.590
He was in the back.

00:07:17.590 --> 00:07:18.920
And I was like, you the best?

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:19.850
And they're like,
shut up, fat boy,

00:07:19.850 --> 00:07:21.510
this isn't a sandwich
eating contest.

00:07:21.510 --> 00:07:23.093
And everybody's like,
laughing at him.

00:07:23.093 --> 00:07:24.777
He's like no, no,
I'm really the best.

00:07:24.777 --> 00:07:26.110
So I said, all right, come here.

00:07:26.110 --> 00:07:26.210
Come here.

00:07:26.210 --> 00:07:27.930
I was like, all right, so
my boy says he's the best.

00:07:27.930 --> 00:07:29.160
We're going to see what happens.

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:30.201
So he plays, and he does.

00:07:30.201 --> 00:07:31.080
He beats everybody.

00:07:31.080 --> 00:07:31.810
He gets a book.

00:07:31.810 --> 00:07:38.319
And what I saw was that racial
barriers, and pecking order--

00:07:38.319 --> 00:07:40.610
you know what I mean, in the
traditional pecking order,

00:07:40.610 --> 00:07:42.380
the obese kid wasn't
really respected.

00:07:42.380 --> 00:07:44.640
But now he was respected.

00:07:44.640 --> 00:07:48.130
And I was like, man, how crazy
is it that all of these kids

00:07:48.130 --> 00:07:51.740
actually know the
game, can play it well,

00:07:51.740 --> 00:07:54.380
but they've made mistakes in
their life that landed them

00:07:54.380 --> 00:07:54.880
here?

00:07:54.880 --> 00:07:56.610
That doesn't even make sense.

00:07:56.610 --> 00:08:01.100
So as I was leaving,
all the rap lyrics

00:08:01.100 --> 00:08:03.640
I ever heard about chess in
that bank that I'd been making,

00:08:03.640 --> 00:08:05.100
they all just hit me.

00:08:05.100 --> 00:08:07.800
And I was like, all right,
all right, this is the thing.

00:08:07.800 --> 00:08:11.140
If I take the rap lyrics
to lure the kids in,

00:08:11.140 --> 00:08:14.330
I can start teaching
them more about chess.

00:08:14.330 --> 00:08:16.390
But then that even
wasn't enough, right.

00:08:16.390 --> 00:08:18.220
I mean, chess is awesome.

00:08:18.220 --> 00:08:19.120
It's a great game.

00:08:19.120 --> 00:08:22.120
It's one of the few global
games that people play.

00:08:22.120 --> 00:08:24.640
If we got on a plane
and went anywhere,

00:08:24.640 --> 00:08:28.220
I guarantee you almost
in any city we landed in,

00:08:28.220 --> 00:08:30.751
we would find some people
playing outside playing chess.

00:08:30.751 --> 00:08:32.500
And then while we were
playing, somebody's

00:08:32.500 --> 00:08:35.380
going to drive by banging
out Jay-Z, banging out

00:08:35.380 --> 00:08:38.049
Wu-Tang, or, know what I'm
saying, 50, whoever, Drake.

00:08:38.049 --> 00:08:41.820
And all of those guys have
mentioned chess in their music.

00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:44.350
So I was like, well,
if chess isn't enough,

00:08:44.350 --> 00:08:46.840
it has to be about life
and stuff like that.

00:08:46.840 --> 00:08:49.520
So at that point, I started
researching chess more.

00:08:49.520 --> 00:08:51.745
And it turned into
what we have now,

00:08:51.745 --> 00:08:53.450
the Hop-Hop Chess Federation.

00:08:53.450 --> 00:08:56.200
And so we don't
just teach chess.

00:08:56.200 --> 00:08:58.020
We have a bunch of
life strategies.

00:08:58.020 --> 00:09:00.120
Some of the life strategies
are in the book--

00:09:00.120 --> 00:09:02.820
the first 12 filters,
different ways

00:09:02.820 --> 00:09:06.000
that you can look at long-
and short-term goal planning,

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.240
look at recovering
from loss, look

00:09:08.240 --> 00:09:13.570
at just being more patient
about the idea of what you can

00:09:13.570 --> 00:09:15.340
do with any given situation.

00:09:15.340 --> 00:09:17.050
And emotional control.

00:09:17.050 --> 00:09:20.240
I was working-- to
create the book,

00:09:20.240 --> 00:09:22.430
I started doing research
by working at a school.

00:09:22.430 --> 00:09:24.096
But I didn't have a
teaching credential,

00:09:24.096 --> 00:09:25.510
so I got in as a security guard.

00:09:25.510 --> 00:09:27.910
And it was crazy.

00:09:27.910 --> 00:09:29.690
I saw crazy stuff going.

00:09:29.690 --> 00:09:33.120
I learned a lot about American
education and its failures

00:09:33.120 --> 00:09:34.360
and some of its strengths.

00:09:34.360 --> 00:09:38.740
But I also mainly learned
a lot about drug abuse,

00:09:38.740 --> 00:09:39.999
alcohol abuse, gangs.

00:09:39.999 --> 00:09:41.290
I learned a lot about violence.

00:09:41.290 --> 00:09:42.956
I learned a lot about
how to communicate

00:09:42.956 --> 00:09:46.670
with kids who are really
active gang members,

00:09:46.670 --> 00:09:48.960
you know what I mean,
or live in those areas.

00:09:48.960 --> 00:09:50.710
And one of the main
things I learned about

00:09:50.710 --> 00:09:53.670
is how many of our children
in America, especially

00:09:53.670 --> 00:09:56.330
in the urban sectors, they
have-- basically they're

00:09:56.330 --> 00:09:58.940
walking around with
post-traumatic stress disorder.

00:09:58.940 --> 00:10:01.802
And it's undiagnosed
and it's untreated.

00:10:01.802 --> 00:10:04.260
And then we're saying, but how
come Johnny doesn't have all

00:10:04.260 --> 00:10:04.570
A's?

00:10:04.570 --> 00:10:06.111
Well, because Johnny's
thinking about

00:10:06.111 --> 00:10:08.930
he might actually catch a bullet
either on the way to school

00:10:08.930 --> 00:10:09.770
or on the way back.

00:10:09.770 --> 00:10:12.520
Or some of these girls, you
know, that carry knives,

00:10:12.520 --> 00:10:15.020
not because they're bad people
but because they get harassed

00:10:15.020 --> 00:10:15.880
and they don't-- you
know what I mean?

00:10:15.880 --> 00:10:17.171
They don't have any protection.

00:10:17.171 --> 00:10:21.450
And so that kind
of stuff, it really

00:10:21.450 --> 00:10:25.170
elevates their stress levels
and their sense of focus.

00:10:25.170 --> 00:10:29.030
And so here we have
this Venn diagram here,

00:10:29.030 --> 00:10:30.980
where you can see
these overlapping

00:10:30.980 --> 00:10:34.730
themes between music,
chess, and martial arts.

00:10:34.730 --> 00:10:37.760
Nonviolence is such a really
big part of what we do,

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:39.870
and we do it through
teaching martial arts.

00:10:39.870 --> 00:10:41.607
A lot of times
when I say we teach

00:10:41.607 --> 00:10:43.690
