00:12:21.470 --> 00:12:25.170
And like, 'cause Amber,
she walked in first,

00:12:25.170 --> 00:12:26.550
and her head was kind of down.

00:12:26.550 --> 00:12:27.920
She was kind of in everything.

00:12:27.920 --> 00:12:30.290
And there were like 12
girls who came to the door.

00:12:30.290 --> 00:12:30.980
And I'm like, what's up?

00:12:30.980 --> 00:12:32.604
And they're like,
we're here for Amber.

00:12:32.604 --> 00:12:35.030
I was like, OK, welcome.

00:12:35.030 --> 00:12:37.210
So they came in, and
they had this huge game,

00:12:37.210 --> 00:12:40.604
and then she won it after
being chased around the board

00:12:40.604 --> 00:12:42.520
with very little material,
but she figured out

00:12:42.520 --> 00:12:44.330
how to outsmart
the dude and win.

00:12:44.330 --> 00:12:46.510
And like the school was nuts.

00:12:46.510 --> 00:12:49.450
And I used to be like, hey, you
guys got to-- it's chess, man.

00:12:49.450 --> 00:12:51.200
They were just too wild.

00:12:51.200 --> 00:12:53.830
So again, unity,
strategy, and nonviolence.

00:12:53.830 --> 00:12:56.085
When you're teaching
chess, you're

00:12:56.085 --> 00:12:57.335
essentially teaching strategy.

00:12:57.335 --> 00:13:00.410
And when you're
teaching, strategy

00:13:00.410 --> 00:13:02.530
comes from a Latin
root word, strategos,

00:13:02.530 --> 00:13:05.360
which means leader of the army.

00:13:05.360 --> 00:13:08.060
That's what chess is about.

00:13:08.060 --> 00:13:09.820
If we want to get
kids out of gangs,

00:13:09.820 --> 00:13:12.590
if we want to get them out of
doing all kinds of wild group

00:13:12.590 --> 00:13:16.410
activities, we need to
help them to be comfortable

00:13:16.410 --> 00:13:19.490
believing in the power
of their own decision

00:13:19.490 --> 00:13:21.470
and trusting their own decision.

00:13:21.470 --> 00:13:27.570
And so leadership is such a
big part of what we do here.

00:13:27.570 --> 00:13:29.420
That's one of my
students right there.

00:13:29.420 --> 00:13:32.490
He's actually blind,
and I currently

00:13:32.490 --> 00:13:34.350
teach him chess and jiu-jitsu.

00:13:34.350 --> 00:13:38.172
And we have a chess and
entrepreneurship class.

00:13:38.172 --> 00:13:39.630
Entrepreneurship
is such a big deal

00:13:39.630 --> 00:13:43.720
because I think as the American
economy and the world economy

00:13:43.720 --> 00:13:45.470
continues to become
more digital,

00:13:45.470 --> 00:13:50.240
that kids can actualize their
ideas for business purposes

00:13:50.240 --> 00:13:51.500
faster than ever.

00:13:51.500 --> 00:13:53.820
And even just their
access to information

00:13:53.820 --> 00:13:55.030
has never been greater.

00:13:55.030 --> 00:13:58.510
So I was meeting with-- I
was talking with some kids

00:13:58.510 --> 00:14:01.660
just last week, and I was
like, my daughter taught

00:14:01.660 --> 00:14:06.212
herself Python between the
ages of like 12 and 14.

00:14:06.212 --> 00:14:07.670
She could make like
80 grand a year

00:14:07.670 --> 00:14:09.128
just based on what
she knows, dude.

00:14:09.128 --> 00:14:11.040
I know you could do
something like that.

00:14:11.040 --> 00:14:12.660
You don't have to
go learn Python,

00:14:12.660 --> 00:14:14.500
but you could do something.

00:14:14.500 --> 00:14:19.850
And so this youngster
here, because he's blind,

00:14:19.850 --> 00:14:24.320
he wanted to create a phone app
that helps people order food,

00:14:24.320 --> 00:14:26.760
because his retinas
don't function.

00:14:26.760 --> 00:14:28.740
So even though he can
kind of walk around--

00:14:28.740 --> 00:14:30.864
sometimes he uses a cane,
sometimes he doesn't-- he

00:14:30.864 --> 00:14:31.820
can't read menus.

00:14:31.820 --> 00:14:35.360
So he created this
idea for an app

00:14:35.360 --> 00:14:38.520
called Eye Menu,
like E-Y-E, Eye Menu,

00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:41.230
and it's going to help
people read menus.

00:14:41.230 --> 00:14:43.900
And it has a Siri
component, so people,

00:14:43.900 --> 00:14:46.520
even if you can't see what's
on the phone, you can hear it.

00:14:46.520 --> 00:14:49.390
And so I helped him put
everything together.

00:14:49.390 --> 00:14:51.140
And then he went
and did this pitch,

00:14:51.140 --> 00:14:53.800
and he was awarded 100,000.

00:14:53.800 --> 00:14:57.800
And so we're working
on the app right now.

00:14:57.800 --> 00:14:59.070
This is me and Tupac.

00:14:59.070 --> 00:15:02.020
That's Pac on the
right, obviously.

00:15:02.020 --> 00:15:05.360
And he was a chess player.

00:15:05.360 --> 00:15:06.420
He was a friend of mine.

00:15:06.420 --> 00:15:07.640
We met that moment.

00:15:07.640 --> 00:15:10.350
We had only known each other
for one minute at that point.

00:15:10.350 --> 00:15:16.020
But we met through the guy on
the left with the polka dots.

00:15:16.020 --> 00:15:18.617
And you know, me and
Pac were always cool.

00:15:18.617 --> 00:15:19.950
You know, he was a chess player.

00:15:19.950 --> 00:15:24.130
And so if you see Mr. Makaveli
moving pieces like telekinesis,

00:15:24.130 --> 00:15:26.720
if it's a chess game, let's
play with real pieces.

00:15:26.720 --> 00:15:29.340
Now that may or may not
make a lot of sense to you,

00:15:29.340 --> 00:15:34.260
but really what that's about is
something that really brought

00:15:34.260 --> 00:15:37.140
me to love chess and this idea
of fusing it with hip-hop,

00:15:37.140 --> 00:15:43.010
and that is that a lot of really
good chess players are in jail.

00:15:43.010 --> 00:15:44.170
They're in prison.

00:15:44.170 --> 00:15:45.770
And if you go look
up, I think it

00:15:45.770 --> 00:15:48.699
was-- was it the
Princeton chess team,

00:15:48.699 --> 00:15:50.240
or I think it was
the Princeton chess

00:15:50.240 --> 00:15:54.755
team went to go play at Rikers
and got housed-- housed, OK.

00:15:57.270 --> 00:15:59.640
But in most prisons,
a lot of wardens

00:15:59.640 --> 00:16:02.290
do not like the
inmates to play chess.

00:16:02.290 --> 00:16:06.410
And they often take the
boards and pieces away

00:16:06.410 --> 00:16:07.510
from the inmates.

00:16:07.510 --> 00:16:10.140
And it seems to be based
around this really stupid idea

00:16:10.140 --> 00:16:13.440
that the algebraic notation,
like when you're playing chess,

00:16:13.440 --> 00:16:16.200
how you move to
e-4, e-5, they have

00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:19.840
this idea that the inmates
will use the algebraic notation

00:16:19.840 --> 00:16:21.150
to do something sinister.

00:16:21.150 --> 00:16:23.520
And then the CO-- I
don't know what it means.

00:16:23.520 --> 00:16:24.590
Oh, there's a riot.

00:16:24.590 --> 00:16:26.660
But that's not going to happen.

00:16:26.660 --> 00:16:28.320
And that's such an insane fear.

00:16:28.320 --> 00:16:29.470
But it's real.

00:16:29.470 --> 00:16:31.690
So a lot of times
they take it away.

00:16:31.690 --> 00:16:34.620
I know inmates who have told
me that they've played chess

00:16:34.620 --> 00:16:36.460
through the wall
with other inmates,

00:16:36.460 --> 00:16:39.420
speaking in algebraic notation.

00:16:39.420 --> 00:16:44.320
Do you realize the cognitive
function in play to do that?

00:16:44.320 --> 00:16:46.290
That's insane, right?

00:16:46.290 --> 00:16:48.730
And so one of the
things-- so when

00:16:48.730 --> 00:16:52.340
he says it's a chess game, let's
play with real pieces, look,

00:16:52.340 --> 00:16:54.050
he didn't say Tupac
was playing, he

00:16:54.050 --> 00:16:55.820
said Makaveli's moving pieces.

00:16:55.820 --> 00:16:56.940
Who's Makaveli?

00:16:56.940 --> 00:16:59.920
Obviously the Italian
philosopher, writer,

00:16:59.920 --> 00:17:02.280
whatever, who made
"The Prince," which

00:17:02.280 --> 00:17:04.089
changed Tupac's
life, which made him

00:17:04.089 --> 00:17:06.609
call himself Makaveli, right?

00:17:06.609 --> 00:17:12.150
So it came to Pac during this
time when he was on lockdown.

00:17:12.150 --> 00:17:16.210
And so he's talking about, I
can play with real pieces now,

00:17:16.210 --> 00:17:17.474
you know what I'm saying?

00:17:17.474 --> 00:17:18.890
Like, let's play
with real pieces.

00:17:18.890 --> 00:17:20.599
I'm no longer in solitary.

00:17:20.599 --> 00:17:22.160
That's the kind of psychology.

00:17:22.160 --> 00:17:27.420
And the reason I mention
that is because so

00:17:27.420 --> 00:17:32.740
many American children
are not getting groomed,

00:17:32.740 --> 00:17:34.990
and not having their
cognitive functions

00:17:34.990 --> 00:17:37.750
enhanced the way
that they could be.

00:17:37.750 --> 00:17:41.780
And so I want more
technology companies

00:17:41.780 --> 00:17:45.250
and I want more
innovators to start

00:17:45.250 --> 00:17:48.080
looking in the hood for
these kinds of people.

00:17:48.080 --> 00:17:52.460
Any kid who could
play blindfolded

00:17:52.460 --> 00:17:54.860
speaking in algebraic
notation, they

00:17:54.860 --> 00:17:58.310
could either be working here
or create the next Google.

00:17:58.310 --> 00:18:03.480
There's a lot of wisdom
in our local community

00:18:03.480 --> 00:18:05.199
that we're not cultivating.

00:18:05.199 --> 00:18:06.740
And it's not their
fault that they're

00:18:06.740 --> 00:18:07.730
from East Side San Jose.

00:18:07.730 --> 00:18:09.190
It's not their fault
that they're from Oakland

00:18:09.190 --> 00:18:09.620
or whatever.

00:18:09.620 --> 00:18:11.411
It's not their fault
they're from East L.A.

00:18:11.411 --> 00:18:14.120
But I know we can do more.

00:18:14.120 --> 00:18:16.650
And so again, chess
and entrepreneurship.

00:18:16.650 --> 00:18:18.990
When I talk to the kids,
Jay-Z, Will Smith, Drake,

00:18:18.990 --> 00:18:23.940
J Cole, 50 Cent, RZA and
GZA, I remind the kids

00:18:23.940 --> 00:18:27.780
that a lot of the top-tier
dudes are chess players.

00:18:27.780 --> 00:18:30.280
But the reason why kids
in hip-hop play chess

00:18:30.280 --> 00:18:32.320
is not to win trophies.

00:18:32.320 --> 00:18:34.980
So like right now, you
know, Magnus Carlsen

00:18:34.980 --> 00:18:36.300
is the world champion.

00:18:36.300 --> 00:18:38.770
If you say, hey, what do
you think of Magnus Carlsen,

00:18:38.770 --> 00:18:40.270
the average kid is going
to shrug their shoulders.

00:18:40.270 --> 00:18:41.103
They don't know him.

00:18:41.103 --> 00:18:43.350
They don't care.

00:18:43.350 --> 00:18:45.880
They don't care because
they don't play chess

00:18:45.880 --> 00:18:46.860
for the same reason.

00:18:46.860 --> 00:18:48.910
They're playing it to get sharp.

