And it was the second
biggest and most diverse

00:22:12.810 --> 00:22:16.604
attended exhibit that they had.

00:22:16.604 --> 00:22:18.020
And so I was really
proud of that.

00:22:18.020 --> 00:22:20.120
I was really proud of that.

00:22:20.120 --> 00:22:23.760
And so the main way
that we teach chess

00:22:23.760 --> 00:22:26.740
is through teaching the
cultural connectivity.

00:22:26.740 --> 00:22:29.237
Like, I went and did a talk at
Harvard School of Education.

00:22:29.237 --> 00:22:31.320
This guy was like-- this
Latino kid came up to me.

00:22:31.320 --> 00:22:34.010
He was like, I really like
your talk, but you know,

00:22:34.010 --> 00:22:36.000
chess is just really an
old white man's game.

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:39.650
I don't understand why you're
using this old white man's game

00:22:39.650 --> 00:22:41.364
to try to teach
kids in the hood.

00:22:41.364 --> 00:22:42.530
That doesn't make any sense.

00:22:42.530 --> 00:22:44.330
And I said, well, I
guess it all starts

00:22:44.330 --> 00:22:45.970
with your
misunderstanding of chess.

00:22:45.970 --> 00:22:48.136
The idea that you think
it's an old white man's game

00:22:48.136 --> 00:22:49.180
is exactly why I teach.

00:22:49.180 --> 00:22:50.596
And he was like,
what do you mean?

00:22:50.596 --> 00:22:53.090
So I said, well, chess
comes from India.

00:22:53.090 --> 00:22:55.810
And then the Arabs learned
it from the Indians,

00:22:55.810 --> 00:22:58.460
and as they raided and traded
through the Horn of Africa

00:22:58.460 --> 00:23:00.110
and came over to West Africa.

00:23:00.110 --> 00:23:01.050
The Africans got it.

00:23:01.050 --> 00:23:04.246
And then in 700 AD, they looked
across the Iberian Peninsula,

00:23:04.246 --> 00:23:07.500
and this German guy had
a problem with someone

00:23:07.500 --> 00:23:09.804
who had attacked his
daughter in Spain,

00:23:09.804 --> 00:23:12.220
and he was like, I think they
got a lot of money in there,

00:23:12.220 --> 00:23:12.720
man.

00:23:12.720 --> 00:23:13.990
You guys should see what's up.

00:23:13.990 --> 00:23:15.970
So the Moors were
like, let's go.

00:23:15.970 --> 00:23:18.172
And they crossed the
Iberian Peninsula.

00:23:18.172 --> 00:23:19.880
And they came in and
they brought algebra

00:23:19.880 --> 00:23:22.390
and they brought the Greek
classics, which they had

00:23:22.390 --> 00:23:23.820
been translating, from Baghdad.

00:23:23.820 --> 00:23:25.160
And they brought chess boards.

00:23:25.160 --> 00:23:28.150
And that's how the Jews and the
Christians started playing it.

00:23:28.150 --> 00:23:31.280
So it goes from Spain
into France and Sicily,

00:23:31.280 --> 00:23:34.100
and then eventually
it goes into England.

00:23:34.100 --> 00:23:39.070
And you know, Benjamin
Franklin is the second American

00:23:39.070 --> 00:23:40.340
by name known to play.

00:23:40.340 --> 00:23:43.300
And he wrote this essay called
"On the Morals of Chess,"

00:23:43.300 --> 00:23:46.010
and it breaks down how
chess helps your character.

00:23:46.010 --> 00:23:49.736
And that small
essay alone totally

00:23:49.736 --> 00:23:52.110
changed my life, like when I
started trying to figure out

00:23:52.110 --> 00:23:54.550
that I'm going to do this.

00:23:54.550 --> 00:24:00.700
And so I said, you know, the
first complete books on chess

00:24:00.700 --> 00:24:01.970
were written by the Muslims.

00:24:01.970 --> 00:24:05.260
But then the Jews innovated
and the Christians innovated,

00:24:05.260 --> 00:24:07.450
and so everybody kind
of owns this game.

00:24:07.450 --> 00:24:10.930
There's not a game that so many
different cultures and races

00:24:10.930 --> 00:24:13.780
and face completely
are connected to.

00:24:13.780 --> 00:24:15.214
And so this is why.

00:24:15.214 --> 00:24:16.880
And he was like,
that's the story of it?

00:24:16.880 --> 00:24:18.170
I was like, yeah,
that's the Cliff Notes.

00:24:18.170 --> 00:24:19.580
I mean, it's much deeper.

00:24:19.580 --> 00:24:21.590
But there's a book called
"The Immortal Game"

00:24:21.590 --> 00:24:23.230
by David Shank you could read.

00:24:23.230 --> 00:24:26.880
And an amazing woman
over at Stanford

00:24:26.880 --> 00:24:28.840
wrote a book called "Birth
of the Chess Queen,"

00:24:28.840 --> 00:24:30.965
about how the chess queen
wasn't an original piece.

00:24:30.965 --> 00:24:32.730
It was the king and his vizier.

00:24:32.730 --> 00:24:36.200
And then over time, as
the more women in Europe

00:24:36.200 --> 00:24:39.030
started taking on
leadership positions

00:24:39.030 --> 00:24:42.129
if the kings would die, the
queen gets on the board.

00:24:42.129 --> 00:24:44.420
And she didn't start that
strong, but little by little,

00:24:44.420 --> 00:24:46.753
over a couple centuries, she
becomes the strongest piece

00:24:46.753 --> 00:24:47.340
on the board.

00:24:47.340 --> 00:24:49.230
Telling that story
to young girls

00:24:49.230 --> 00:24:50.880
totally changes their posture.

00:24:50.880 --> 00:24:52.680
I see them sit up more.

00:24:52.680 --> 00:24:54.345
And we say, look,
you know, it's not

00:24:54.345 --> 00:24:55.720
enough to just
say you're a king,

00:24:55.720 --> 00:24:57.428
or it's not enough to
say you're a queen.

00:24:57.428 --> 00:24:59.896
Kings and queens move
in very specific ways.

00:24:59.896 --> 00:25:01.270
So when you're
out on the street,

00:25:01.270 --> 00:25:02.980
you can't just act any way.

00:25:02.980 --> 00:25:05.610
You have to know that
queens don't move like that.

00:25:05.610 --> 00:25:07.380
You have to move like a queen.

00:25:07.380 --> 00:25:10.330
And then you will see
differences in your grades,

00:25:10.330 --> 00:25:12.820
and you know what I mean, who
you are around and all that.

00:25:12.820 --> 00:25:15.540
And so it's been a great ride.

00:25:15.540 --> 00:25:20.935
So BobbyBruceAndTheBronx.com
is coming.

00:25:20.935 --> 00:25:24.790
I just got a few more swaps.

00:25:24.790 --> 00:25:29.980
And there's Emmanuel right
after he got his award,

00:25:29.980 --> 00:25:32.740
and we're working on
Eye Menu right now.

00:25:32.740 --> 00:25:35.180
We have a summer
camp we're doing.

00:25:35.180 --> 00:25:38.249
And he learns jiu-jitsu, too.

00:25:38.249 --> 00:25:40.290
He's going to have his
