00:25:40.290 --> 00:25:43.460
in about four weeks in Alameda.

00:25:43.460 --> 00:25:45.385
And we're starting
to slowly grow.

00:25:45.385 --> 00:25:47.260
The other thing I want
to add before I finish

00:25:47.260 --> 00:25:49.800
is just that one of the other
things that I've learned

00:25:49.800 --> 00:25:52.140
is I started intending
this to take it

00:25:52.140 --> 00:25:53.900
to black and Latino
kids in the hood.

00:25:53.900 --> 00:25:55.674
That was my original
plan, because I

00:25:55.674 --> 00:25:57.590
felt like a lot of the
American school systems

00:25:57.590 --> 00:25:59.860
were ignoring them,
and there weren't

00:25:59.860 --> 00:26:02.880
enough African-American
philanthropists

00:26:02.880 --> 00:26:04.210
or whatever to help them.

00:26:04.210 --> 00:26:07.600
So that's why I created this.

00:26:07.600 --> 00:26:09.302
At risk-- so if I say
at risk, you know,

00:26:09.302 --> 00:26:11.010
you're thinking, you
know, Latino guy who

00:26:11.010 --> 00:26:13.640
might be a gang member,
or a black dude who

00:26:13.640 --> 00:26:16.240
might be a crack dealer or
weed dealer or whatever.

00:26:16.240 --> 00:26:17.820
That was my intention.

00:26:17.820 --> 00:26:21.190
After I created it and the more
that I started engaging kids,

00:26:21.190 --> 00:26:24.950
I realized that there was the
separate group of at-risk kids,

00:26:24.950 --> 00:26:27.550
and they actually tend
to be white and Asian.

00:26:27.550 --> 00:26:36.020
And they're actually just--
I was kind of loud and crazy,

00:26:36.020 --> 00:26:37.625
but I was a nerd
when I was a kid.

00:26:37.625 --> 00:26:39.500
But there are a lot of
kids who are just kind

00:26:39.500 --> 00:26:40.924
of quiet and
reserved, and parents

00:26:40.924 --> 00:26:42.340
will start bringing
me their kids,

00:26:42.340 --> 00:26:45.220
and they'd be like,
hey, this is my son.

00:26:45.220 --> 00:26:47.230
When he comes home, he
just sits in his room.

00:26:47.230 --> 00:26:47.980
He doesn't go out.

00:26:47.980 --> 00:26:48.646
He doesn't talk.

00:26:48.646 --> 00:26:49.970
He doesn't do anything.

00:26:49.970 --> 00:26:52.600
And I'm worried about him.

00:26:52.600 --> 00:26:55.050
He hasn't done anything,
you know what I mean,

00:26:55.050 --> 00:26:57.130
but he doesn't talk.

00:26:57.130 --> 00:26:59.190
He sits in his room all day.

00:26:59.190 --> 00:27:02.260
So I sat down with him,
talk to him about chess,

00:27:02.260 --> 00:27:04.000
get him to play a little bit.

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:05.910
I know he's not
necessarily thrilled

00:27:05.910 --> 00:27:08.350
about the idea of doing
jiu-jitsu because he's small

00:27:08.350 --> 00:27:11.250
and he's not really engaging,
but I get him on the mat.

00:27:11.250 --> 00:27:15.220
And now these kids are totally
different human beings.

00:27:15.220 --> 00:27:18.040
And what I'm finding is
that this second group

00:27:18.040 --> 00:27:22.550
of at-risk kids, they're a
lot bigger than we thought.

00:27:22.550 --> 00:27:25.000
At the school that I was at
originally in San Francisco,

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:29.360
it was so wild with fights, with
blacks and Latinos and kids who

00:27:29.360 --> 00:27:31.000
were cutting
themselves and kids who

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:35.280
were drinking and just wild,
that a lot of the Asian kids

00:27:35.280 --> 00:27:37.100
aren't even considered,
right, because it's

00:27:37.100 --> 00:27:39.700
like, as long as they're not
trying to shoot up the school

00:27:39.700 --> 00:27:42.799
or start a fight,
we're happy with them.

00:27:42.799 --> 00:27:44.840
But we don't know what's
happening in their head.

00:27:44.840 --> 00:27:46.660
Like, that kid might
want to jump off

00:27:46.660 --> 00:27:47.800
the third floor right now.

00:27:47.800 --> 00:27:49.280
We have no idea.

00:27:49.280 --> 00:27:52.610
So I would always refer to the
Asian kids as the invisibles,

00:27:52.610 --> 00:27:54.650
because just because
they were quiet,

00:27:54.650 --> 00:27:59.280
just because they were getting
A's, didn't mean they were OK.

00:27:59.280 --> 00:28:02.080
And the school was
OK with, as long

00:28:02.080 --> 00:28:03.830
as they weren't
actively fighting,

00:28:03.830 --> 00:28:05.500
we didn't worry about them.

00:28:05.500 --> 00:28:09.910
And so I think that there is
this second group of at-risk,

00:28:09.910 --> 00:28:15.300
socially withdrawn kids, boys
and girls, that I'm noticing

00:28:15.300 --> 00:28:17.220
in schools and in
America, and I think

00:28:17.220 --> 00:28:20.974
that we should be working
on helping them as well.

00:28:20.974 --> 00:28:22.390
You know, we need
to start working

00:28:22.390 --> 00:28:23.510
on helping them as well.

00:28:23.510 --> 00:28:27.880
And I think that chess is
just such a great tool.

00:28:27.880 --> 00:28:30.590
It raises cognitive function.

00:28:30.590 --> 00:28:33.460
Kids who study chess
have-- their math grades

00:28:33.460 --> 00:28:34.960
are 15% higher.

00:28:34.960 --> 00:28:36.760
Reading comprehension goes up.

00:28:36.760 --> 00:28:38.470
There's so many
studies-- not even

00:28:38.470 --> 00:28:40.469
recent studies, studies
that go all the way back

00:28:40.469 --> 00:28:42.580
to the '70s that
talk about this.

00:28:42.580 --> 00:28:43.970
And chess is so cheap.

00:28:43.970 --> 00:28:46.320
There's no reason
we shouldn't have it

00:28:46.320 --> 00:28:50.514
in every school every day across
America, especially when, I

00:28:50.514 --> 00:28:51.930
mean, you've seen
the test scores.

00:28:51.930 --> 00:28:53.090
Our kids need help.

00:28:53.090 --> 00:28:54.280
Our kids need help.

00:28:54.280 --> 00:29:00.110
And this is absolutely
a great tool.

