00:29:28.930 --> 00:29:32.502
that they respond to that
maybe other programs,

00:29:32.502 --> 00:29:34.960
other activities kids could
get involved with doesn't have?

00:29:34.960 --> 00:29:36.240
Is it about personal attention?

00:29:36.240 --> 00:29:37.560
Is it the subject matter
is interesting to them?

00:29:37.560 --> 00:29:38.270
ADISA BANJOKO: You
know what it is?

00:29:38.270 --> 00:29:40.630
I mean, most of the kids--
that's a great question,

00:29:40.630 --> 00:29:45.820
and I think the first part
is just-- there's two things.

00:29:45.820 --> 00:29:49.070
One, I don't think-- even a lot
of nonprofits that mean well,

00:29:49.070 --> 00:29:50.870
I think that they
don't connect with kids

00:29:50.870 --> 00:29:53.590
because they're afraid of
who they're trying to help.

00:29:53.590 --> 00:29:55.710
So, we've got this great
after-school program,

00:29:55.710 --> 00:29:58.260
but don't beat me up.

00:29:58.260 --> 00:30:02.880
And so you can't teach
kids you're afraid of.

00:30:02.880 --> 00:30:06.150
And the other part is,
you can't judge them.

00:30:06.150 --> 00:30:10.740
So I didn't come in saying,
hey, so what's up, dude?

00:30:10.740 --> 00:30:13.140
You look like you're a
Norteno, what's going on?

00:30:13.140 --> 00:30:13.850
You want to sit?

00:30:13.850 --> 00:30:14.630
I don't do that.

00:30:14.630 --> 00:30:17.592
I just play chess.

00:30:17.592 --> 00:30:19.050
And then little by
little, they see

00:30:19.050 --> 00:30:20.754
that the judgment isn't there.

00:30:20.754 --> 00:30:22.420
And then they'll be
like, man, you know,

00:30:22.420 --> 00:30:23.660
I just stopped smoking weed.

00:30:23.660 --> 00:30:24.300
Oh, for real?

00:30:24.300 --> 00:30:24.570
OK.

00:30:24.570 --> 00:30:25.444
You know what I mean?

00:30:25.444 --> 00:30:26.537
And you know, that's it.

00:30:26.537 --> 00:30:28.870
That may be the only thing
you get for like two weeks is

00:30:28.870 --> 00:30:30.530
that they stopped smoking weed.

00:30:30.530 --> 00:30:33.420
And then you'd just
be like, you smoking?

00:30:33.420 --> 00:30:34.250
No?

00:30:34.250 --> 00:30:35.310
OK, cool.

00:30:35.310 --> 00:30:36.820
All right, that's good.

00:30:36.820 --> 00:30:38.400
Don't smoke.

00:30:38.400 --> 00:30:40.000
And little stuff like that.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:43.040
And so I think it's just
the human engagement.

00:30:43.040 --> 00:30:44.750
What I'm finding
is a lot of kids,

00:30:44.750 --> 00:30:47.860
whether they're withdrawn,
like some of my newer students,

00:30:47.860 --> 00:30:53.090
or whether they're gang impacted
or very active in the streets,

00:30:53.090 --> 00:30:57.380
the lack of judgment and
the consistent engagement

00:30:57.380 --> 00:30:58.610
is what makes it happen.

00:30:58.610 --> 00:31:00.310
That's what makes it turn.

00:31:00.310 --> 00:31:02.170
And then when you're
playing with them

00:31:02.170 --> 00:31:04.210
and you're talking
about, well, why did you

00:31:04.210 --> 00:31:05.310
move the knight there?

00:31:05.310 --> 00:31:06.935
What did you think
was going to happen?

00:31:06.935 --> 00:31:07.990
Then you're helping them.

00:31:07.990 --> 00:31:12.582
Because chess is helping
them reassess their flaws,

00:31:12.582 --> 00:31:14.290
and that's a hard
thing for anyone to do.

00:31:14.290 --> 00:31:17.420
And they're using chess
as a filter to self-assess

00:31:17.420 --> 00:31:18.820
and reassess.

00:31:18.820 --> 00:31:21.230
And then when you help
them without judging them,

00:31:21.230 --> 00:31:22.827
they want to learn more.

00:31:22.827 --> 00:31:23.660
That's what I think.

